### Tested versions

- Reproducible in a1591512f8c3a211b5fc94770fd64e3dbc825630 onward (PR #107782 onward)
- Not Reproducible in 4.4.1 (but hard to test because it has a separate issue: #108948)

### System information

Godot v4.5.beta (967e2d499) - Windows 11 (build 26100) - Multi-window, 1 monitor - Vulkan (Mobile) - dedicated NVIDIA GeForce RTX 3060 Laptop GPU (NVIDIA; 32.0.15.7260) - Intel(R) Core(TM) i7-10750H CPU @ 2.60GHz (12 threads) - 15.82 GiB memory

### Issue description

#107782 introduced a new way of applying the debanding dither: in the `blit.glsl` shader of `renderer_compositor_rd.cpp`.

As far as I can tell, this new location for applying the viewport debanding filter works well, but to view the change in the editor, the editor must first be restarted. This issue is specific to the editor when HDR 2D is enabled.

It was difficult to tell whether this was an issue with #107782 before Calinou discovered the source of a longstanding issue in #108950. After applying the fix from #108950, it becomes clear that there is a remaining issue that is specific to #107782.

### Steps to reproduce

To be honest, the easiest way to reproduce this is with a custom editor build that modifies `tonemap.glsl` to the following:

```
	if (bool(params.flags & FLAG_USE_8_BIT_DEBANDING)) {
		// Divide by 255 to align to 8-bit quantization.
		color.rgb += screen_space_dither(gl_FragCoord.xy, 255.0);
		color.r = 1.0;
	} else if (bool(params.flags & FLAG_USE_10_BIT_DEBANDING)) {
		// Divide by 1023 to align to 10-bit quantization.
		color.rgb += screen_space_dither(gl_FragCoord.xy, 1023.0);
		color.r = 1.0;
	}
```

and modify `blit.glsl` to the following:

```
		if (data.use_debanding) {
			color.rgb += screen_space_dither(gl_FragCoord.xy);
			color.b = 1.0;
		}
```

This way, any tonemapper-based dithering is easy to see as a red tint and any blit-based debanding is easy to see as a blue tint. When using this approach, you will find that when HDR 2D is enabled, the editor needs to be restarted to match the game's (correct) behaviour.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

Here is a MRP that works well with the above editor changes.

[editor-hdr2d-debanding-needs-restart.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21435110/editor-hdr2d-debanding-needs-restart.zip)

### Tested versions

v4.4.1.stable.mono.official [49a5bc7b6]
Blender 4.3

### System information

Godot 4.4.1.stable.mono - Windows 11 - Forward+ -  Vulkan - RTX 3060 - Blender 4.3

### Issue description

My plan is to group vertices by giving them unique vertex colors, so that I can later refer them by their COLOR in the vertex function and animate them in group in gdshader.

The problem is that the COLOR is not the same as how I specified them in Blender 4.3.

For example, I have a plane (2 x 7 vertices), with 2 vertices on each column specified a color
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/82be7019-bb8a-4fac-96cd-2f7c284f83ee)

Then I import to Godot, and debug view the color by only painting the fragment colors if its vertex color is near those specified color (except color black [0,0,0])

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/efb2b57c-5429-4298-a193-70a86f012d18)

Wireframe view:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/e0b2d892-74a5-4924-a9f8-2f752949ce31)

Shader code:
```
shader_type spatial;
render_mode cull_disabled, unshaded;

void vertex() {
}

void fragment() {
	ALBEDO=vec3(0.0);
	const float margin=0.05;
	if (length(COLOR.rgb-vec3(0.2,1.0,0.0))<margin)
		ALBEDO=COLOR.rgb;
	else if (length(COLOR.rgb-vec3(0.4,1.0,0.0))<margin)
		ALBEDO=COLOR.rgb;
	else if (length(COLOR.rgb-vec3(0.6,1.0,0.0))<margin)
		ALBEDO=COLOR.rgb;
	else if (length(COLOR.rgb-vec3(0.8,1.0,0.0))<margin)
		ALBEDO=COLOR.rgb;
	else if (length(COLOR.rgb-vec3(1.0,1.0,0.0))<margin)
		ALBEDO=COLOR.rgb;
}
```

I was able to fix by powering the COLOR by 0.42 in vertex function, but not sure if it applies to all situation.
```
void vertex() {
	//somehow power color by 0.42 works
	COLOR=pow(COLOR,vec4(0.42));
}
```

<img width="458" height="428" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/4ac58d61-1d63-4c29-bbd9-96a66f9c5378" />

Wireframe:

<img width="425" height="431" alt="Image" src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fe19d590-7554-4904-9057-9c5c070b2784" />



### Steps to reproduce

In Blender 4.3:
1. Create a plane mesh and subdivide them in Blender.
2. In Data>Color Attributes. Add a color attribute.
3. In Edit mode, select some random vertices.
4. In Vertex Paint, choose random colors.
5. Paint>Set Vertex Colors. Dont use the brushes, it will blend with other colors.
6. Export mesh with vertex color data.

In Godot 4.4.1:
1. Add ShaderMaterial to mesh.
2. Insert the code above, but change the color comparision to your expected color.

### Minimal reproduction project (MRP)

[mrp_vtx_color.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21395084/mrp_vtx_color.zip)

This PR fixes a crash when closing a scene when a node is selected. This code:

```cpp
for (Node *node : node_previous_selection) {
	node->disconnect(CoreStringName(script_changed), callable_mp(this, &SceneTreeDock::_queue_update_script_button));
}
```

crashed on `node->disconnect` because `node` is a previously freed object by the time this runs.

I considered validating the objects like in PR #108791, but we should really properly clear out the selection instead. I also saw PR #108785 after writing this, and both accomplish the same thing, except that this PR clears out SceneTreeDock's previously selected nodes at the same time as EditorSelection itself is cleared of those nodes.

*Bugsquad edit:* Fixes #108783 Supersedes #108791 Supersedes #108785
